The meeting is the "Framework Agreement for Peace, Security and Co-operation in the DRC and the Region," indicates a note from the Angolan Foreign Ministry. The document said that upon arrival, Minister Téte António was received by the Angolan ambassador to the DRC, Miguel Costa, who was accompanied by Angola's diplomatic representative in Kenya, Sianga Abílio. The meeting of Foreign Ministers comes ahead of the 10th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the signatory countries of the Framework Agreement for Peace, Security and Co-operation in the DRC, to be held in a face-to-face format next Thursday 24. The event will review progress made in the implementation of the Framework Agreement and will be chaired by the Head of State of the DRC. President Felix Tshisekedi will assume the Oversight Mechanism for a one-year term, currently held by Ugandan Head of State, Yoweri Museveni. Angola will participate in the Summit in its dual capacity as a signatory to the Framework Agreement and as Chair-in-Office of the International Conference on the Great Lakes Region (ICGLR). In this capacity, Angola will sit in the official rostrum with the host President, Félix Tshisekedi, the Secretary-General of the United Nations, António Guterres, the Chairperson of the African Union Commission, Moussa Faki, and the Chairperson-in-Office of the Southern African Development Community (SADC), Lazarus Chakwera. The Framework Agreement for Peace, Security and Co-operation in the DRC and the Region was signed on 24 February 2013 in Addis Ababa (Ethiopia). Initialling the Framework Agreement were Angola, Burundi, Kenya, Central African Republic, Congo, Democratic Republic of Congo, Rwanda, South Africa, Sudan, South Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda and Zambia. This agreement was also signed by the United Nations, African Union, SADC, ICGLR, European Union, Belgium, United States America, France and United Kingdom. --ChannelAfrica--